Policies are deny-by-default. A token can only touch paths a policy explicitly grants. You write them in HCL, mapping paths to capabilities (create, read, update, delete, list).
```hcl
path "secret/data/myapp/*" {
  capabilities = ["read"]
}
path "database/creds/readonly" {
  capabilities = ["read"]
}
```
```bash
vault policy write myapp-ro policy.hcl
```
Keep policies tight and per-app. Do not grant `secret/*` to everything because it was easier. The whole point of Vault is that a compromised app can only reach the handful of secrets it was supposed to have.

Vault Agent is a sidecar or daemon that handles auth and secret delivery so your app code does not have to speak the Vault API. It auto-authenticates, caches and renews tokens, and can render secrets into files from templates.
```hcl
auto_auth {
  method "approle" { ... }
}
template {
  source      = "db.tpl"
  destination = "/etc/secrets/db.env"
}
```
The app just reads `/etc/secrets/db.env` like any config file, and the Agent keeps it fresh and re-renders when the secret rotates. This is the cleanest way to add Vault to an app you do not want to rewrite. In Kubernetes, the Vault Agent Injector adds this sidecar automatically through pod annotations.
